kv.site_description: This is a ~12 acre hay field that receives horse manure spread on it daily, Nov-April, every year since 2010. Seeding has not occurred for several years. Almost a monoculture of Orchard Grass at this point. Area is flat.The field gets cut 2 times per year with a yield of 450-520 bales per year with most recent years seeing steady increase. The annual amount of manure spread is ~700 tons, which equates to almost 10 tons per month (during the ~6 month period) per acre. Some Seldan Spray is used as a spot spray against broadleaf plants once or twice per year.
kv.general_observations: Very low diversity.  Orchard grass predominates.

kv.site_description: level, formerly irrigated ground just south of Harlan lane. Pomegranates taken out 2016, row crops 7 years before that, seeded in winter 2016-17 to beardless wheat and some native grasses, cut for silage and then grazed with sheep. This section was flooded in late summer by leakage from nearby ditch. Ground cover variable: bare, ryegrass, groundcherry, russian thistle sprouts.
kv.general_observations: Annual ryegrass, groundcherry, knotweed, barnyard grass, pomegranate sprouts, russian thistle sprouts, clover--vegatation patchy and not well distributed. About half or more of land is bare here. Moist soil from recent wetting from ditch leakage, clay soil has surface cracks. Soil samples in 4 x 4m plot show high variability in terms of clay color: dark with yellow streaks, blue streaks, some of the yellowish clay has orange mottles, plus some very sandy pockets. Because of visible variability of soil cores, this site may not be best for measuring soil change over time.

From: Lance Gunderson <Lgunderson@wardlab.com>

To: "Holly.Utrata-Halcomb@hamilton-co.org" <Holly.Utrata-Halcomb@hamilton-co.org>
Subject: Re: Haney Info
Hi Holly, 

I too am confused by what I am looking at in more ways than one.  First, the P test from MSU is done using a Bray 1 extraction, so this P value would be even higher if they used a Mehlich 3 extraction, which the H3A from the Haney Test has been correlated to.  The second confusing part of this is that they are recommending additional P be applied and you should have ample P available at those test levels.  They are also requesting a lot of N, but I don't see a soil test level for N evaluated on their report so I don't know how they are determining how much N you need to apply unless they are simply assuming no N in your soil to start with.  

When I convert Mg from the Haney Test I get a value of 354, which is pretty close to the value they give you for 388.  I take the 186 * 1.4281 + 88.197 to get 354.  K is a little different.  Your test result on the Haney test is pretty low at 32, which converted is about 82, a little more than half of what they measured at MSU.  At a value of 32 we are getting pretty low on our calibration curve.  We don't normally see samples read quite that low and our conversion is likely a little better when we start with values around 100 up to 200 or so.  Above 200 on the Haney Test and we don't recommend K.  For Ca we stared with 1024 ppm on the Haney test, which equates to 2466 ppm using the conversion equation.  This actually isn't too bad for a comparison with the 2094 you got from MSU.  

Again, P is the biggest difference I see here.  As part of the Haney Test we evaluate P on 2 different extracts (you only see the H3A value, but the other is a water extract) using 2 different sets of calibration standards and 2 different pieces of analytical equipment.  Both the Lachat, which measures H3A extractable inorganic P, and the ICAP, which measures total H3A extractable P, gave us much lower numbers than what is reported by MSU.  

If we still have the sample, I am going to re-run the P portion of the test to double check our numbers and I will do this at no additional charge.  Hopefully, we still have the sample, and if so, I will be in touch when we have some more values for the re-runs.

kv.unit1:
1-day CO2-C:
National 4 year average is 52 ppm
This result is one of the most important numbers in the soil test procedure. This value is the amount of CO2-C (ppm) released in 24 hr. from soil microbes after your soil has been dried and rewetted (as occurs naturally in the field). This is a measurement of the microbial activity in the soil and is highly related to soil fertility. In most cases, the higher the number, the more fertile the soil.
kv.unit2:
Soil Health Calculation:
National 4 year average is 9.3
This number is calculated as 1-day CO2-C / 10 + WEOC/100 + WEON/10 to include a weighted contribution of microbial activity, water extractable organic C and N. It represents the overall health of your soil system. It combines 5 independent measurements of your soil’s biological and chemical properties. The calculation looks at the balance of soil C and N and their relationship to microbial activity. This soil health calculation number can vary from 0 to more than 50. We like to see this number increase over time. This number indicates the current soil health and helps us identify what it needs to reach its highest sustainable state. Keeping track of this Soil Health number will allow you to gauge the effects of your management practices over the years.
